Props
------
Props are used to pass data from a parent component to a child component in React. They are read-only and cannot be
modified by the child component. Props allow you to make components reusable and dynamic.

- Props are way to pass args to components
- Props are using HTML-like attributes syntax


Example:
------> ChildComponent.jsx
```javascript
import React from 'react';

const ChildComponent = ({ name="Child" }) => {
  return <div>Hello from {name}</div>;
};
export default ChildComponent;
```


-----> ParentComponent.jsx
```javascript
import React from 'react';
import ChildComponent from './ChildComponent';

const ParentComponent = ({ name = "Parent" }) => {
  return (
    <div>
      <ChildComponent name={name} />
    </div>
  );
};
export default ParentComponent;
```


-----> App.jsx
```javascript
import React from 'react'
import ParentComponent from './components/ParentComponent'
import ChildComponent from './components/ChildComponent'

function App() {
  return (
    <>
      <div>
        <h3>{'<ParentComponent name="John" /> output: '}</h3>
        <ParentComponent name="John" />
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3>{'<ParentComponent /> output: '}</h3>
        <ParentComponent />
      </div>

      <br></br>
      <br></br>

      <div>
        <h3>{'<ChildComponent text="Anna" /> output: '}</h3>
        <ChildComponent name="Anna" />
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3>{'<ChildComponent /> output: '}</h3>
        <ChildComponent />
      </div>
    </>
  )
}

export default App
```

OUTPUT:
<ParentComponent name="John" /> output:  Hello from John
<ParentComponent /> output:  Hello from Parent

<ChildComponent text="Anna" /> output: Hello from Anna
<ChildComponent /> output: Hello from Child



Hooks
------
Hooks are functions that let you use state and other React features in functional components. They allow you to manage
state, lifecycle events, and side effects without needing to convert your component to a class.

The idea behind React hooks is to let you use state and other React features in functional components, without needing
to write class components. Before hooks, if you wanted to manage component state or tap into lifecycle methods, you had
to write a class. Hooks changed all that by providing a way to “hook into” React features directly in your functions.

Here are the core ideas:
- useState lets you add and update local state inside a functional component.
- useEffect allows you to run side effects (like fetching data, updating the DOM, or setting timers) when your component
  renders or updates.

Hooks make your code cleaner and easier to reuse by separating logic into smaller functions.
So instead of this:
```javascript
class Counter extends React.Component {
  state = { count: 0 }
  componentDidUpdate() {
    document.title = `Count: ${this.state.count}`
  }
  render() {
    return <button onClick={() => this.setState({ count: this.state.count + 1 })}>{this.state.count}</button>
  }
}
```

You can do this:
```javascript
function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  useEffect(() => {
    document.title = `Count: ${count}`;
  }, [count]);

  return <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>{count}</button>;
}
```


Another example:
-----> HooksCounter.jsx
```javascript
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function HooksCounter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);   // useState creates a state variable count

  useEffect(() => {                        // useEffect updates the page’s title whenever count changes
    document.title = `Count: ${count}`;
  }, [count]);

  const increment = () => setCount(prevCount => prevCount + 1);
  const decrement = () => setCount(prevCount => prevCount - 1);

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Count: {count}</h2>
      <button onClick={increment}>Increment</button>
      <button onClick={decrement}>Decrement</button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default HooksCounter;
```


-----> App.jsx
```javascript
import React from 'react'
import HooksCounter from './components/HooksCounter'

function App() {
  return (
    <>
       <div>
           <h3>{'Hooks Counter output: '}</h3>
            <HooksCounter />
       </div>
    </>
  )
}

export default App
```

OUTPUT:
Hooks Counter output:         Count: 3
                        Increment    Decrement



State
------
State is a built-in object in React that allows you to create components that can change their output over time.

Example:
-----> StateClickCounter.jsx
```javascript
import React, { useState } from 'react';

function StateClickCounter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  const handleClick = () => {
    setCount(prev => prev + 1);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <p>You clicked {count} times!</p>
      <button onClick={handleClick}>Click Me</button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default StateClickCounter;
```


-----> App.jsx
```javascript
import React from 'react'
import StateClickCounter from './components/StateClickCounter'

function App() {
  return (
    <>
      <div>
        <h3>{'State Click Counter output: '}</h3>
        <StateClickCounter />
      </div>
    </>
  )
}

export default App
```

OUTPUT:
State Click Counter output:     You clicked 1 times!
                                      Click Me

Explanation:
- useState(0): Creates a state variable count initialized to 0.
               React keeps track of this value even after the component re-renders.
- setCount(prev => prev + 1):  Updates the state when the button is clicked.
                               Triggers a re-render so the new count appears in the UI.

- Dynamic UI:  The paragraph updates automatically whenever count changes.
               There’s no manual DOM manipulation—React handles it under the hood.



State vs Hooks: What's the Difference?
----------------------------------------
1. State is a concept
State is simply data that changes over time and influences what your component displays.
Think of it as the memory of your component.

2. Hooks are tools to use that state
Hooks like useState, useReducer, or useRef are functions introduced in React 16.8 that let you use features like state
and side effects in function components—something that was previously only possible in class components.

Example Analogy:
State is like a whiteboard for your component.
useState hook is the marker you use to write on it—and React watches that board to update the UI when the writing changes.


